attributes.body:
I was surprised when I first arrived, mostly because I had no idea what a tourist town it was going to be. There are many hostels and hotels sprinkled everywhere. Despite this, it's still quite nice. There's lots of good food, it's affordable, and it's surrounded by loads of greenery.

Most of my time here was just spent doing some day hikes, finding curious things to eat, and generally wandering around to meet other travelers.

photos.title: Sean's Ass
photos.description: This ass just ran up to us. I was actually a little concerned at first. But she just wanted some attention.

photos.title: Cory and Ass
photos.description: What a cutie.

photos.title: Donkey
photos.description: She seemed really concerned when we walked away.

photos.title: Baños Town
photos.description: This was on the hike with Sean.

photos.title: Erupcion
photos.description: There was a minor eruption when we were up on the hill with the casa del arbol. We heard a rumble and all ran over to the edge to see a giant plume of smoke slowly rising. I feel very lucky to have seen it.

photos.title: Tree Swing
photos.description: Proper tree swing, somehow it held together.

photos.title: Handstand Battle
photos.description: We battled, I lost.

photos.title: Chill Spot
photos.description: Some music, some beers, some soft grass, and a bit too much sun. All in all, a great day.

photos.title: New Friends
photos.description: We picked up Florian on the road (The German dude on the right).

photos.title: Tomates de Arbol
photos.description: These are the tree tomatoes growing on the side of the hill. In general they're pureed and put in juice with a bit of sugar. They taste a bit like tomatoes but much more sour, and a touch earthy. It really does make for some fantastic juice.

photos.title: Baños Valley
photos.description: This is the town from up on the hill.

photos.title: Salt Water Toffee
photos.description: A bunch of guys pull toffee all day. It tastes exactly how you would expect it to.

photos.title: Cuy Guinea Pig
photos.description: Here's some cuy, which is just grilled guinea pig. I wanted some, but wasn't hungry when we passed by. We came back later to get a plate, but they were closed. The woman in the background is somewhat unamused, though I did ask about taking photos before going to town.

photos.title: Cuy
photos.description: You can see his little teeth in this one.

photos.title: Evelyn
photos.description: I went out for beers with a couple of buddies, and suddenly evelyn disappeared into a piercing shop...

photos.title: Church
photos.description: Yet another church, this one had great carvings on the door.

photos.title: Church Carvings
photos.description: You can't see all of the carvings, but they're quite impressive.

photos.title: Sugar Cane
photos.description: This is something I've seen over and over in latin america, and confuses me to no end. Each of those blue booths is selling the same sugar cane, for the same price, in the same booth...

photos.title: Chifles
photos.description: You've got your roasted corn, something like a soybean, fried plantain chips, salsa, and a cocktail sauce. Quite good, and probably the healthiest street food I've ever had.

photos.title: Chifles Vendor
photos.description: I had seen this around and wanted to try it, so I walked over to where a police officer was getting her chifles, and asked her what they were. She told me, and then she offered me a bite with her own spoon. I thought it a bit odd because in the states I feel like police try to separate themselves to keep a sense of authority. But no, she gave me a spoonful of chifles, I promply bought my own, it was quite good.

photos.title: Waterfall
photos.description: This waterfall feeds the hot springs cold water. There are pools of cold water in which to cool off after a long soak.

photos.title: Hot Springs
photos.description: It doesn't look good from here, but at night, when it's full of people it's quite nice.
